To send the body in a POST HTTP request using Angular, you need to use the `HttpClient` module provided by the `@angular/common/http` package. Here is an example of how to do it:

1. Import the HttpClient module in your component or service file:
```typescript
import { HttpClient, HttpHeaders } from '@angular/common/http';
```

2. Inject the HttpClient module in your component or service constructor:
```typescript
constructor(private http: HttpClient) { }
```

3. Create and send the POST request with the desired body:
```typescript
const url = 'http://example.com/api/endpoint';
const body = { name: 'John', age: 30 };
const headers = new HttpHeaders().set('Content-Type', 'application/json');

this.http.post(url, body, { headers }).subscribe(response => {
  console.log(response);
}, error => {
  console.error(error);
});
```

In the above example, replace `http://example.com/api/endpoint` with your actual API endpoint URL, and `body` with the data you want to send in the request body.

Make sure to set the `Content-Type` header to `'application/json'` or the appropriate content type for your API.

Also, don't forget to subscribe to the HTTP request to actually send it, and handle the response or error in the subscribe function.

Note that this example assumes you have already configured the necessary HTTP headers or interceptors for authorization and other requirements, if any.

